      "content": "Let's dive back into the science.\n\nThe benthic zone is the lowest layer of a body of water, extending from the surface to the seafloor. The pressure and light conditions in this zone are extreme, with pressures increasing by about 1 atmosphere for every 10 meters of depth. This is equivalent to being about 1 kilometer below the surface.\n\nIn terms of light, the amount of sunlight that reaches the seafloor is limited, and it's often described as \"dim\" or \"dappled.\" This limited light supports a unique community of organisms that have adapted to survive in these conditions.\n\nOne of the key challenges in the benthic zone is finding food. Since there are no plants to produce organic matter, animals in this zone must rely on other sources of nutrition. Some examples of benthic zone animals that have adapted to this challenge include:\n\n* Giant tube worms, which use chemosynthesis to produce their own food. They have symbiotic bacteria that live inside their bodies and convert chemicals from the seafloor into energy.\n* Sea cucumbers, which are detritivores that feed on dead and decaying organic matter on the seafloor. They use their many tentacles to capture",
